portion in <span class='question-badge'>35</span> <input type='text' id='ans-35' style='width: 180px; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #ced6e0; border-radius: 6px; outline: none;'> and mineral.</li></ul><h3 style='color: #2f3542; margin-top: 25px; border-left: 4px solid #e84393; padding-left: 10px;'>Research methods:</h3><ul style='list-style-type: none; padding-left: 5px;'><li style='margin-bottom: 12px;'>• 36. Scientists can learn their <span class='question-badge'>36</span> <input type='text' id='ans-36' style='width: 180px; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #ced6e0; border-radius: 6px; outline: none;'> pattern in Atlantic ocean.</li><li style='margin-bottom: 12px;'>• 37. Scientists can start tracking when the turtle reaches <span class='question-badge'>37</span> <input type='text' id='ans-37' style='width: 180px; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #ced6e0; border-radius: 6px; outline: none;'></li><li style='margin-bottom: 12px;'>• 38. Huge front flipper can produce <span class='question-badge'>38</span> <input type='text' id='ans-38' style='width: 180px; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #ced6e0; border-radius: 6px; outline: none;'> from strong muscles.</li><li style='margin-bottom: 12px;'>• 39. A new recorder can monitor not only their location but also the <span class='question-badge'>39</span> <input type='text' id='ans-39' style='width: 180px; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #ced6e0; border-radius: 6px; outline: none;'> in the sea.</li><li style='margin-bottom: 12px;'>• 40. Leatherback turtles are found using more <span class='question-badge'>40</span> <input type='text' id='ans-40' style='width: 180px; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #ced6e0; border-radius: 6px; outline: none;'> to search food.</li></ul></div>"
